    "narrative": "For today's slate, **Cal Raleigh** (71.30) and **Will Smith** (70.62) anchor our offensive production, benefiting significantly from favorable platoon matchups and top-of-the-order positioning. **Cal Raleigh** is our highest-rated asset, leveraging a +10% SP skill adjustment against the lefty Liberatore, while **Will Smith**\u2019s score is buoyed by a +5% wind-out factor and an assumed #3 spot. **Geraldo Perdomo** also presents as a high-upside play at 68.05; his +19% SP skill boost against the high-xERA M\u00e1rquez makes him a priority start, though he carries the only significant weather concern of the day with a 36% rain risk. **Bryson Stott** (66.12) and **Jonathan Aranda** (65.19) round out the top tier, both capitalizing on positive dynamic platoon splits against right-handed pitching.\n\nThe most difficult decision for the lineup optimizer involved **Gleyber Torres**, who narrowly missed the cut with a 50.43 score. Despite his favorable #2 lineup projection, a -13% penalty on his dynamic platoon split against Singer ultimately relegated him to the bench in favor of higher-efficiency hitters. Conversely, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** remains in the starting lineup with a 59.41 despite a poor 26-PA BvP history against Gausman, as his base projection and favorable park factor provide enough floor to trust his elite skill set. \n\nWe are monitoring the status of **Geraldo Perdomo** and **Gavin Sheets** closely, as the concurrent 36% rain risk for their respective contests poses a potential disruption to our daily efficiency goals. While **Jung Hoo Lee** (50.33) and **Wenceel Perez** (44.34) occupy the bottom of our starters, their inclusion is primarily driven by the need to exploit the stolen base environment created by Eury P\u00e9rez\u2019s slow delivery, keeping them ahead of bench pieces like **Yainer Diaz** and **Lawrence Butler**, who lack the same situational leverage today.",
